{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f09e4bb-1c17-4a8e-a7ef-6470fe4c606e","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen implement it with a real class for production:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\nIn your classes, **inject `IFileSystem`** instead of calling `File`/`Directory` directly. In tests, mock it or use an in-memory fake.\n\n**Alternatively**, the [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) NuGet package provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface covering the full `System.IO` surface, plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing — saves you from maintaining your own wrapper.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dc29ffae-0377-4b06-b85d-ecda6b4bfc9e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET project. This is a design/architecture question about abstracting file system dependencies for testability. Let me provide a concise answer based on best practices.","outputTokens":344,"requestId":"4C15:14E17:D4E58A:1056A80:6A01364A"},"id":"b97f3ead-bbd9-45da-93c8-e2f4fc1664ca","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:52:18.901Z","parentId":"364f8cec-1e90-4cad-9575-60ac46c67d9f"}
